{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778267989,"nonce":"/8xiB6gh1arBSfLsbc51XZQ9GgQ=","title":"8-state cs_faithful_pointmass + 50ms delay augmentation; analytical-side structural lift","message":"## Motivation\n\nRe-review of cs2019.pdf identified two structural gaps in our analytical Riccati setup that are likely the load-bearing reasons our maximum analytical Δv tops out at +2.12% while C\u0026S Fig 1e (visually re-measured at 125 vs 116 px) shows ~+7.8%. See findings: /tmp/flavor_ab_review/findings/cs2019_review.md.\n\nReference: Crevecoeur \u0026 Scott 2019, J Neurosci 39(41):8135–8148. ModelDB 258846 source: minmaxfc_pointMass.m, AugRobustControl.m.\n\n## Gap 1 (G6) — 8-state plant with disturbance-integrator coupling\n\nCurrently cs_faithful_pointmass uses a 6-state plant ([px, py, vx, vy, fx, fy]) with B_w = I_6 applied directly: each sample of ε_t directly perturbs velocity for one step (impulsive).\n\nC\u0026S use 8 states. Rows 7,8 are pure integrators (rows of A all zero) driven only by D = I_8, so x_7 = ∫ε_7 dt and x_8 = ∫ε_8 dt. Then A[3,7] = A[4,8] = 1 couples the integrated disturbance INTO velocity. Effect: the disturbance enters velocity as a smooth cumulative drift, not as impulsive noise. The worst-case ε under H∞ is structurally different (smooth growing function vs high-frequency impulse train), and the optimal controller must respond more aggressively → higher peak velocity inflation.\n\nThis is a structurally different H∞ game, not just a parameter tweak.\n\n## Gap 2 (G1) — 50ms (5-step) sensorimotor delay augmentation\n\nTrained controllers use feedback_delay_steps = 5 (50ms) in scripts/train_minimax.py:285. C\u0026S analytical also uses 50ms via shift-register state augmentation: (h+1)·n state vector with delayed observation. Our analytical has no delay augmentation at all.\n\nThis is structurally inconsistent with both our trained side AND C\u0026S analytical side. Easy fix: lift state by h·n = 5·n_obs additional states implementing a tap-delay shift register.\n\n## Implementation\n\n- Extend cs_faithful_pointmass to take a delay_steps kwarg (default 5) and a disturbance_integrator kwarg (default True).\n- 8-state form: append two integrator states; modify A so rows 7,8 are zero, A[3,7] = A[4,8] = 1; modify D = I_8 so disturbance enters states 7,8 only; extend Q to weight integrator-state cost (or set entries 7,8 to zero).\n- Delay augmentation: append (delay_steps · n_obs) lag states implementing y_t = state_{t-delay}; controller observes the delayed state.\n- Keep the 6-state no-delay version reachable for backward compatibility / debugging via kwargs.\n\n## Reframed Δv target\n\nUser measurement of Fig 1e: 125 px (robust) vs 116 px (LQG) → +7.76%. Update synthesis §4.2-revised, §5.4 to cite this measurement and stop treating \"+10–15%\" as the target. Note: C\u0026S text never reports numerical Δv anywhere — text quotes are about cost (~15% higher robust cost, p.8139), not velocity.\n\n## Tests\n\n- Re-run analytical Δv after the 8-state lift + delay augmentation; expect convergence toward +7–8% on canonical 15cm reach.\n- Compare to current 6-state-no-delay numbers (+1.00% at 1.5γ\\*; +2.12% at 1.05γ\\*).\n- Sanity: 8-state with disturbance-integrator on but delay=0 should still differ from current setup; isolate the contribution of each gap.\n\n## Cross-references\n\n- Stage 0 of phase umbrella f695729: 03a148a — this is a structural refinement of that work.\n- Synthesis: results/flavor_a_vs_b/synthesis.md §4.2-revised, §5.4.\n- Codex prior review: /tmp/flavor_ab_review/codex_chat_substantive.txt (assistant turn 14:00:58 cited ModelDB code).\n- Hypothesis-by-hypothesis evaluation: /tmp/flavor_ab_review/findings/cs2019_review.md (G1–G7 with disposition).\n\n## Deprioritized hypotheses (documented for record)\n\n- G2 Kalman estimator: not in their analytical Riccati path per ModelDB. Defer.\n- G4 cost-schedule scaling: matches on shared 6 entries; trivial extension after G6.\n- G5 horizon (600ms vs 800ms): small effect, deprioritized per user.\n- G7 motor/system noise (α₂, α₃): not active in published-figure run; averaged out across 100 sims.","files":null}]}